snippet.textDisplay: Rebuilding cylinders aren’t to hard. Just a lot of fluids. I do them all the time in the military on engineer equipment. Just ensure you get a full cylinder rebuild kit. Your gonna want a couple of equipment to hold the ram. The ram seals sometimes have a hidden pin under the seals. You can use the pump to push out the ram or crack the lines and pull it out. The wiper seal is at the end where it extends. You can use a pipe wrench to remove it, if you can’t find a wrench big enough. Usually you will have to have a big cheater pipe to help get them off. Too tell if the engine is a two stroke, Detroit uses a supercharger on the two strokes. Two strokes require a forced induction to pressurize the cylinders.

snippet.textDisplay:
I suggest running a test again with pops rig. Leave it lifted for an hour and do a measurement from solid floor of dropped boom.
Hydraulic systems are designed to slowly drop in the event of failure.
Testing is done at maximum safe working load(SWL) at highest lifting level allowing for dropping of the Boom.
Cracks in the forks are more dangerous than a leaking hydraulic system!!!!

snippet.textDisplay:
i maintained a lift just like this one for 30years. 1st off,no electronics in this machine,4-53 Detroit about 100HP on a good day.. 2. Rule#1: never stand under the mast/boom or get into the engine bay with the boom up in the air without a safety prop on the lift cylinders. If you don't have one,make one.There were two versions of this machine,one with a two-piece boom and a model with a three-piece boom; a street tire machine like you have,2WD and a 4WD,4wheel steer loader tire machine version. Two speeds on the engine,either idling or flat to the floor wide open.
Anemic and underpowered.Basic 16,000lb capacity boom retracted all the way in.
